 to the cross-validation metrics, then your model is overfitting. If it performs poorly on both, then it is underfitting. This is one way to tell when a model is too simple or too complex.\n","\n","Another way is to look at the **learning curves**: these are plots of the model's performance on the training set and the validation set as a function of the training set size (or the numbr of training iteration). To generate the plots, simply train the model several times on different sized subsets of the training set. The following code defines a function that plots the learning curves of a model given some training data:\n"],"metadata":{"id":"5lNpyPs1nTqI"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve, LearningCurveDisplay\n","from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","\n","display = LearningCurveDisplay.from_estimator(\n","    poly_reg,\n","    X_poly,\n","    y.ravel(),\n","    train_sizes = np.linspace(0.01, 1.0, 10), # try different train size n\n","    scoring=\"neg_root_mean_squared_error\", #evaluation criterion\n","    cv=5,  # 5-fold cross-validation to compute out-of-sample performance\n","    score_type=\"both\")"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"v3500mBnn28_","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771451824640,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":426,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"ee210602-7b60-4115-c26e-ba2125ca962f"},"execution_count":62,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["This deserves a bit of explanation. First, let's look at the performance on the training data: when there are just one or two observations (instances) in the training set, the model can fit them perfectly, which is why the curve starts at zero. But as new observations (instances) are added to the training set, it becomes impossible for the model to fit the training data perfectly, both because the data is noisy and because it is not linear at all. So the score on the training data goes down until it reaches a plateau, at which point adding new observations to the training set doesn't make the average score much better or worse. Now let's look at the performance of the model on the validation data. When the model is trained on very few training observations (instances), it is incapable of generalizing properly, which is why the validation score is initially quite small. Then as the model is shown more training examples, it learns and thus the validation score slowly goes up. However,\n","once again a straight line cannot do a good job"],"metadata":{"id":"M79TJ5SksafA"}}]}